<br>
Don't go with a system where mods are reviewed. It's prone to problems and hurt feelings, or reviewing with the sole purpose of either retaining or ousting a mod. <br>
<br>
Don't go with a &quot;mod keeps forum unless someone challenges&quot;.  This leads to ones who might wish to mod being intimidated by the entrenched mod, particularly if the mod is either a real good mod, or a popular one.<br>
<br>
Do go with some sort of rotation. This is the fairest way. At the evil board (<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) we do the four month rotation for admins. I think it's fantastic. I was an admin for 6 months (special case, not the usual) and by the end, I couldn't get off of admin quickly enough. (although, ironically, I had to NAG the two in charge to let me go! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <br>
<br>
After having the month off, I felt GREAT and was ready to come back. Had it been permanent, I think I would have eventually burned out to the point where I would have never done it again.<br>
<br>
Plus - you get new blood in with a rotation, can have different ones come in and out. So instead of only a few mods, you have more of a selection, folks are rested and not stressed and cliques don't form.<br>
<br>
That's just my opinion, take it if it helps. Good luck on whatever you choose. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>------------------<br>
